      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Empirical backing is mixed, as the long-term effects of major tax reforms are notoriously difficult to isolate from other economic shifts. Proponents often point to historical examples where deregulation and tax cuts spurred investment, leading to broader job gains. Critics counter with data showing that benefits often disproportionately flow to capital owners, not necessarily wage earners in the long run. Therefore, current literature suggests the outcome is highly sensitive to implementation details and concurrent policy environments.",
      "source": "target",
