      "content": "A prevailing view among mainstream economists suggests that while tax cuts can boost short-term incentives for investment, the magnitude of long-term growth depends heavily on how that capital is deployed. Many neoclassical models predict growth through increased supply, but contemporary empirical work often tempers this optimism by highlighting diminishing returns to capital. Consequently, many economists view the \"trickle-down\" argument as an outcome that is not guaranteed without accompanying structural reforms.",
